<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Visual Effect Event Point
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        Spawns one or more visual effects at a mission location, either as always-on scenery or as scripted feedback when another Event Point fires.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        What Visual Effect Event Points Do
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        A <Bold>Visual Effect</Bold> Event Point creates visible feedback such as fire, flares,
        shockwaves, smoke trails, or a combined explosion-style effect. It is used when the mission
        needs something visible in the world rather than only a sound, message, or state change.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Visual Effect Event Points are often placed directly on the thing they represent: a fire,
        an explosion point, a damaged object, or a location that should visually respond to mission
        progress. They can be permanent, or they can wait for another Event Point to activate them.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Practical meaning:</Run>
                <Run> Use Visual Effect for world feedback the player can see. Pair it with Sound Effect, Message, Activate Prim, Create Bomb, or objective logic when the visual needs context.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Common Properties
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Visual Effect uses the standard Event Point common properties: index number, Event Point
        type, letter group, colour, position, facing direction, trigger settings, and listening mode.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The index number and Event Point type are automatic. Letter group and colour are useful for
        keeping a visual effect grouped with the objective, prop, enemy, bomb, or trigger chain that
        causes it.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Position
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Position controls where the effect appears in the world. Place the Event Point at the exact
        source of the visual: the fire location, explosion point, impact point, or damaged object.
        Altitude matters, so check the Y value if an effect appears buried, floating, or clipped by
        nearby geometry.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Trigger Settings
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Trigger settings decide when the visual appears. A trigger of <Bold>None</Bold> with
        <Bold>Active</Bold> is useful for ambient effects that should exist from mission start.
        <Bold>Dependency</Bold> is useful for scripted reveals, explosions, fires, and objective
        feedback after another Event Point has fired.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Visual Effect-Specific Settings
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Visual Effect has two type-specific settings. <Bold>Data[0]</Bold> stores a bitmask of the
        selected effect types, so multiple effects can be enabled at once. <Bold>Data[1]</Bold>
        stores the effect scale.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Effect Types</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Effect Types is a multi-select bitmask. You can choose one effect, such as
        <Bold>Bonfire</Bold>, or combine several effects for a larger explosion-like result.
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="40,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Flare</Bold> - a bright light burst.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Fire Dome</Bold> - a dome-shaped fire expansion.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Shockwave</Bold> - an expanding shockwave ring.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Smoke Trails</Bold> - rising smoke particles.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Bonfire</Bold> - a persistent burning fire effect.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Scale</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Scale controls the size or intensity of the effect and is clamped by the editor to
        <Bold>0-1024</Bold>. Existing missions commonly use <Bold>0</Bold> for default scale and
        <Bold>256</Bold> for deliberately larger or stronger effects.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Authoring tip:</Run>
                <Run> For a simple standing fire, choose only Bonfire. For an explosion or impact moment, combine Flare, Fire Dome, Shockwave, Smoke Trails, and optionally Bonfire.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        How Missions Trigger Visual Effects
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Existing Visual Effect usage is mostly split between ambient fires that are active from the
        start and scripted effects that are activated by another Event Point. Useful trigger patterns
        are:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>None</Bold> - use for always-on ambience, especially Bonfire effects.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Dependency</Bold> - use when another Event Point should cause the visual to appear.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Boolean OR</Bold> - use when any one of several related conditions can reveal the same visual result.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Enemy Radius</Bold> - use when an enemy entering or reaching an area should cause the effect.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Active</Bold> - the observed listening mode for Visual Effect entries; use it for normal one-shot or always-on activation.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2" CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Critical setup detail:</Run>
                <Run> If no Effect Types are selected, the Event Point has no visible effect. Choose at least one effect type before testing the trigger chain.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Common Visual Effect Patterns
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Ambient Fire</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>None</Bold> and <Bold>Active</Bold> when the effect should exist as soon as the
        mission starts. This is the most common pattern for Bonfire effects used as scenery,
        hazards, or atmospheric fires.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>Acarry.ucm</Bold>, Visual Effect <Bold>102</Bold> is a <Bold>Bonfire</Bold> with
        trigger <Bold>None</Bold> and listening mode <Bold>Active</Bold>. It has no dependency and
        appears as part of the mission setup.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">How to author it</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Add a Visual Effect at the fire location, select <Bold>Bonfire</Bold>, leave the trigger as
        <Bold>None</Bold>, and use <Bold>Active</Bold>. Use Scale only if the default-sized fire is
        too small for the scene.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Scripted Explosion Or Impact</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Dependency</Bold> when the effect should appear after a bomb, objective, prim,
        camera moment, or other scripted Event Point. Combining several effect types gives a fuller
        explosion-style result.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>Bankbomb1.ucm</Bold>, Visual Effects <Bold>16-20</Bold> combine
        <Bold>Flare</Bold>, <Bold>Fire Dome</Bold>, <Bold>Shockwave</Bold>,
        <Bold>Smoke Trails</Bold>, and <Bold>Bonfire</Bold>. They all use
        <Bold>Dependency</Bold> on Event Point <Bold>9</Bold>, creating multiple visual points from
        the same mission trigger.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">How to author it</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Create the Event Point that represents the cause first, such as a bomb or objective trigger.
        Place one or more Visual Effect Event Points around the affected area, select the combined
        effect types, then set <Bold>Triggered By</Bold> to <Bold>Dependency</Bold> and point
        <Bold>EP Ref</Bold> at the causing Event Point.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Scaled Effect Cluster</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use Scale when the default effect is not large or strong enough. Scale is especially useful
        when several effects are distributed across an area and need to read clearly during gameplay.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>e3.ucm</Bold>, Visual Effects <Bold>77</Bold> and <Bold>78</Bold> combine all five
        effect types at <Bold>Scale 256</Bold>. They are triggered by <Bold>Dependency</Bold> on
        Event Point <Bold>76</Bold>, so the larger effects appear only after that mission condition.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">How to author it</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Start with the desired effect types at default scale, test the placement, then increase Scale
        gradually. Keep related Visual Effect points grouped by colour and letter so the cluster is
        easy to inspect later.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Conditional Fire Reveal</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Boolean OR</Bold> when several mission branches can lead to the same fire or visual
        state. This lets the effect appear if any linked condition becomes true.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>botanicc.ucm</Bold>, Visual Effects <Bold>139-141</Bold> are
        <Bold>Bonfire</Bold> effects triggered by <Bold>Boolean OR</Bold> referencing Event Point
        <Bold>138</Bold>. This pattern is useful when a visual state can be caused by more than one
        route through the mission logic.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Enemy-Triggered Effect</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Enemy Radius</Bold> when the visual should appear because an enemy reaches or
        enters an area. This is less common, but useful for encounter scripting and area-based
        mission events.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>skymiss2.ucm</Bold>, Visual Effect <Bold>349</Bold> combines all five effect types
        and uses <Bold>Enemy Radius</Bold> with radius <Bold>352</Bold>, referencing Event Point
        <Bold>313</Bold>. The effect is therefore tied to an enemy-related spatial condition.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Basic Visual Effect Workflow
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Decide whether the effect is ambient or triggered by mission logic.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Add a <Bold>Visual Effect</Bold> Event Point at the exact world location.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Select one or more <Bold>Effect Types</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set <Bold>Scale</Bold>, leaving it at 0 for default size unless a larger effect is needed.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>For ambient effects, use <Bold>None</Bold> and <Bold>Active</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>For scripted effects, use <Bold>Dependency</Bold> and set <Bold>EP Ref</Bold> to the Event Point that causes it.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Test in 2D and 3D views to confirm the position, altitude, and trigger timing.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Pair with Sound Effect or Message if the player needs stronger feedback.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2" CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Final checklist:</Run>
                <Run> At least one effect type is selected, Scale is intentional, the Event Point is placed at the correct altitude, and the trigger matches whether the effect should be ambient or scripted.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

</FlowDocument>
